<article>
    <h1>In rare</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200822/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-22"><time>2020-08-22</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline">Nir&#xAD;mal Ghosh&#xD;&#xA;US Bureau Chief In Wash&#xAD;ing&#xAD;ton</span>
    </section>

    <p>The Demo­cratic Party, de­mor­alised in 2016, may have US Pres­i­dent Don­ald Trump to thank for uni­fy­ing it.</p>
    <p>What was ev­i­dent from four days of the Demo­cratic National Con­ven­tion (DNC) – that had a sur­real fu­tur­is­tic ring to it in this pan­demic era as can­di­dates spoke in empty halls or in their own homes, but to mil­lions of peo­ple – is that the party is much more united than in 2016.</p>
    <p>Ver­mont’s so­cial­ist Sen­a­tor Bernie San­ders pub­licly and firmly en­dorsed Mr Joe Bi­den as the party’s nom­i­nee for pres­i­dent.</p>
    <p>Mr San­ders was, for a while, Mr Bi­den’s most se­ri­ous chal­lenger in the pri­maries, and in 2016 was less than en­thu­si­as­tic in his sup­port for then Demo­cratic pres­i­den­tial can­di­date Hil­lary Clin­ton.</p>
    <p>A re­cur­ring mes­sage at the vir­tual con­ven­tion, watched in homes, on­line and on gi­gan­tic out­door screens set up in carparks, was the need to vote.</p>
    <p>Get­ting peo­ple to vote is ev­ery­thing. Democrats re­main haunted by the fact that in 2016, Mrs Clin­ton won the pop­u­lar vote</p>

